\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\family typewriter
ADMBP
\family default
 (ARDL Dynamic Multiplier Bootstrap Package) is a collection of gretl scripts
 to estimate ARDL (autoregressive distributed lag) models and associated
 bootstrap coefficients as well as bootstrap dynamic multipliers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This function package comprises the following features:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Automatic lag selection of optimal ARDL model based on information criteria
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Estimation of unconditional and conditional ARDL models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bootstrap coefficient estimates using 4 different bootstrap procedures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Computation of bootstrap dynamic multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Computation of bootstrap error-correction coefficients and bootstrap long-run
 dynamic multipliers under the assumption of cointegration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Inference on long-run multipliers using either the bootstrap method or Bewley's
 IV approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In case you want to test for a long-run cointegrating relationship between
 the series of interest, I recommend to use the gretl user-written function
 package 
\family typewriter
cointARDL (LINK: 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://sites.google.com/site/arturtarassow/code/ardl-bootstrap-cointegration"

\end_inset

)
\family default
 which comprises two bootstrap based tests using the single-equation cointegrati
on framework.
 The help file of the 
\family typewriter
cointARDL 
\family default
package can also be seen as a supplement to this help file.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another user-written function package for gretl comprising facilities to
 compute dynamic multipliers was recently published by Oleh Komashko.
 His 
\family typewriter
lagreg
\family default
 function package shares a few ideas with our package.
 Both packages provide useful tools.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The ARDL model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Begin with the ARDL(1,1) in levels model 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\phi_{1}y_{t-1}+c_{0}x_{t}+c_{1}x_{t-1}+u_{t},\quad t=1,...,T
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset

 are unknown parameters, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{t}=x_{t-1}+e_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where both 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 are some error terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ARDL model can be re-written in the 
\emph on
error-correction
\emph default
 ECM(-ARDL) form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta y_{t} & =-(1-\phi_{1})\left[y_{t-1}-\frac{c_{0}+c_{1}}{1-\phi_{1}}\right]+c_{0}\Delta x_{t}+u_{t}\\
 & =\rho(y_{t-1}-\beta x_{t-1})+c_{0}\Delta x_{t}+u_{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho=-(1-\phi_{1})$
\end_inset

 denotes the so called error-correction coefficient (speed of adjustment
 back to the long-run attractor).
 The model is dynamically stable as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $|\rho|=|1-\phi_{1}|<1.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general level ARDL(p,q) model (here without any deterministics) can
 be written as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\sum_{j=1}^{p}\phi_{j}y_{t-j}+\sum_{j=0}^{q}c_{j}x_{t-j}+u_{t}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 denote the respective lag length.
 In case the lowest lag of the exogenous regressor is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{min}>0$
\end_inset

 a so called 
\emph on
unconditional
\emph default
 ARDL is estimated.
 If the contemporaneous value 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 is included, the so called 
\emph on
conditional
\emph default
 ARDL is specified (for details see Pesaran/Shin, 1999).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following assumptions are made:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}\sim iid(0,\sigma_{u}^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a general linear stationary process with zero mean and finite variance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 are uncorrelated for all lags such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 is strictly exogenous w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $|\phi_{1}|<1,$
\end_inset

 so that the model is dynamically stable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All model parameters are estimated by OLS using gretl's internal
\family typewriter
 ols
\family default
 command.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dynamic multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cumulative dynamic multiplier effects of 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 at horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 are evaluated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m_{h}=\sum_{j=0}^{h}\frac{\partial y_{t+h}}{\partial x_{t}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $h\to\infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{h}$
\end_inset

 converges to the 
\series bold
long-run multiplier
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=-\frac{c_{0}+c_{1}}{\rho}$
\end_inset

 .
 In case the conditional ARDL is estimated, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the so called 
\series bold
impact multiplier
\series default
.
 Bootstrap confidence intervals are computed similarly to the algorithm
 explained in the following sub-section 2.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Inference on long-run multipliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the ARDL framework, the long-run multiplier is a 
\emph on
non-linear
\emph default
 transformation.
 In the literature, the null hypothesis that the long-run multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}=0$
\end_inset

 is usually tested by means of the Delta method which is an approximation.
 Typically, however, the Delta method yields rather poor approximation.
 We offer two alternatives to compute the standard deviation of the long-run
 multipliers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Bootstrap inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using bootstrap sampling we can estimate the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The algorithm works as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Box Boxed
position "t"
hor_pos "c"
has_inner_box 1
inner_pos "t"
use_parbox 0
use_makebox 0
width "100col%"
special "none"
height "1in"
height_special "totalheight"
thickness "0.4pt"
separation "3pt"
shadowsize "4pt"
framecolor "black"
backgroundcolor "none"
status open

\begin_layout Enumerate
Estimate the ARDL(
\begin_inset Formula $p,q$
\end_inset

) model for fixed lags 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 by OLS
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\sum_{j=1}^{p}\phi_{j}y_{t-j}+\sum_{j=0}^{q}c_{j}x_{t-j}+u_{t}
\]

\end_inset

 and store all coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\phi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c_{i}}$
\end_inset

 , and the estimated residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}_{t}$
\end_inset

 where the initial values are taken to be fixed in the statistical sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Construct the bootstrap sample, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y_{t}^{\ast}\}$
\end_inset

, recursively from the first step with 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 randomly drawn bootstrap errors, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{t}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

, generated using re-centered residuals, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}_{t}^{c}:=\hat{u}_{t}-T^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{T}\hat{u}_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The same initial values are used for each generated series, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{-p+1,\ldots,}^{\ast}y_{0}^{\ast}=y_{-p+1,\ldots,}y_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Using the bootstrap sample, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y_{t}^{\ast}\}$
\end_inset

, estimate the ARDL(
\begin_inset Formula $p,q$
\end_inset

) model using OLS.
 Check for dynamic stability.
 If stability is ensured proceed with the next step, otherwise go back to
 step 2 and draw from another set of residuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given the bootstrap parameter estimates, compute the long-run multiplier
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Repeat steps 1 to 4 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the standard deviation of all 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 bootstrap long-run multipliers 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Resampling is done by means of gretl's fast 
\family typewriter
resample()
\family default
 function.
 In future versions of this package, we may make use of gretl's MPI toolbox
 to accelerate computations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Bewley's IV approach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bewley proposed an alternative representation (see Bewley, 1979 and Hassler/Wolt
ers, 2006) of the ARDL model according to which the long-run multipliers
 of vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\beta}$
\end_inset

 are just the coefficients of vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 His idea is based on an IV regression using lags of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 as valid instruments.
 This estimation is automatically done by the 
\family typewriter
Bewley()
\family default
 function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 2SLS estimates, we rely on gretl's native 
\family typewriter
tsls
\family default
 function using the 
\family typewriter
--robust
\family default
 option to compute HAC standard errors per default.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bootstrap variants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The user can choose between 4 bootstrap methods.
 In the 
\family typewriter
ADMBP
\family default
 package we generate for each replication an artificial data set of the
 same length as the original data set on the assumption that the estimated
 version of the core model is the true data-generating process, using the
 observed initial values of each variable, the estimated model, and a set
 of random innovations.
 These innovations can be obtained using 4 different ways.
 The 
\emph on
parametric
\emph default
 bootstrap draws from a normal distribution.
 The 
\emph on
non-parametric
\emph default
 bootstrap re-samples with replacement from the estimated residuals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate the two semiparametric wild bootstrap approaches, start from
 the wild bootstrap DGP 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}^{\ast}=X_{t}\tilde{\beta}+f(\tilde{u}_{t})v_{t}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\beta}$
\end_inset

 denotes the least squares estimates, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\tilde{u}_{t})$
\end_inset

 is a transformation of the 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{th}$
\end_inset

 residual 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{u}_{t}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 is a random variable with mean 0 and variance 1.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For further details, see e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "russell-davidson.arts.mcgill.ca/e761/rd-jgm-bootstrap.pdf "
target "russell-davidson.arts.mcgill.ca/e761/rd-jgm-bootstrap.pdf "

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\emph on
wild uniform
\emph default
 bootstrap assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 is drawn from a uniform distribution.
 In contrast, the Rademacher two-point distribution is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v_{t}^{\ast} & =\begin{cases}
-1 & \text{{with\quad probability}\; 0.5}\\
1 & \text{{with\quad probability}\; 0.5}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The stationary block-bootstrap was proposed by Politis/Romano (1994).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The work was published as Dimitris N.
 Politis and Joseph P.
 Romano: The Stationary Bootstrap, 
\emph on
Journal of the American Statistical Association
\emph default
, Vol.
 89, No.
 428 (Dec., 1994), pp.
 1303-1313.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This bootstrap attempts to mimic time-dependency in the time-series.
 The mean block-size is determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $b=round(1.75\times T^{1/3})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 denotes the sample length.
\end_layout

