\begin_layout Subsection
Determine the optimal lag length
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first step of the modeling stage comprises the determination of the optimal
 lag length of the approximate ARDL specification.
 The function 
\family typewriter
lagselect()
\family default
 makes use of gretl's 
\family typewriter
var
\family default
 command to determine the lag length using some standard information criteria.
 For the determination of the lag length, only variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 enters as an endogenous while all other variables are taken as exogenous.
 A simple example follows using the AWM-macroeconomic dataset comprising
 various series observed at a quarterly frequency over 28 years.
 The objective is to estimate a consumption equation where real log consumption
 expenditures, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t},$
\end_inset

 is supposed to be a linear but dynamic function of its own lags as well
 as the log of real income, 
\begin_inset Formula $inc_{t}$
\end_inset

, and log of real wealth, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For illustrative purposes we set the maximum lag length to 
\begin_inset Formula $p=q=4$
\end_inset

.
 Note that at the moment, the 
\family typewriter
ADMBP
\family default
 package does not allow for gappy lag structures and the same lag length
 applies to all variables — which is also the standard case in VAR modeling.
 In the example we use the AIC information criteria to determine the optimal
 lag length.
 However, the user has the choice of using the BIC or the HQ criteria alternativ
ely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
