\begin_layout Standard
This function computes the error-correction term 
\emph on
aka
\emph default
 the cointegrating relationship, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{t}$
\end_inset

, using the respective bootstrap median long-run coefficients.
 To be more concrete, assume that variables 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 are both I(1) variables and cointegrated where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 refers to the long-run coefficient such that the error, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{t}$
\end_inset

, is also stationary:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta_{t}=y_{t}-\beta x_{t}.
\]

\end_inset

 The literature discusses the following five cases
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{\textbf{(I)} no constant:\;} & \zeta_{t}=y_{t}-\beta x_{t}\\
\text{\textbf{(II)} restr. const.+no trend}:\; & \zeta_{t}=y_{t}-\beta x_{t}-\delta_{0}/\rho\\
\text{\text{\textbf{(III)} unrestr. const+no trend}:\;} & \zeta_{t}=y_{t}-\beta x_{t}\\
\text{\textbf{(IV)} unrestr. const +restr. trend:\;} & \zeta_{t}=y_{t}-\beta x_{t}-\delta_{1}/\rho\\
\text{\textbf{(V)} unrestr. const.+unrestr. trend:\;} & \zeta_{t}=y_{t}-\beta x_{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{0}$
